OL,3,C'Plonker, prat and numpty': Study
OL,4,Cshows classic British insults dying out
OL,6,F"Prat", another common British insult,
OL,7,Fbelieved to have originated from the
OL,8,FOld English word "prtt", meaning
OL,9,Ftrick or prank, was unknown to a
OL,10,Fquarter of the age group.
OL,12,FThe term "Nitwit", meaning someone
OL,13,Fparticularly stupid had not been heard
OL,14,Fof by 27%, according to research
OL,15,Fagency, .
OL,17,FFans of Only Fools and Horses may wish
OL,18,Fto look away as 25% had no idea that
OL,19,Fthe term "plonker" was used as an
OL,20,Finsult - or "put downs", as Gen Z
OL,21,Fwould call them.
