OL,3,C'Plonker, prat and numpty': Study
OL,4,Cshows classic British insults dying out
OL,6,FNearly half of Brits under the age of
OL,7,F28 (47 percent) had not heard of the
OL,8,Finsult "cad", which refers to an
OL,9,Funreliable character - particularly a
OL,10,Fman who has behaved badly with
OL,11,Fdisregard to women.
OL,13,FOther more regional insults fared even
OL,14,Fworse. The East Anglian term for a
OL,15,Fclumsy oaf "Lummox" had not been heard
OL,16,Fby 62% of young Brits - and a majority
OL,17,Fof Brits overall (54%).JThe Scots term
OL,18,F"bampot" meaning a fool was unknown to
OL,19,Fsix in ten of the younger generation.
OL,20,FInterestingly even in Scotland, 20% of
OL,21,Fpeople were unsure of its meaning.
